Harry Potter Episodes 5 and 6 - Wizardâ€™s chess - Predict who wins in chess

This tutorial is adapted from Brian Liâ€™s chess modelling tutorial.

Explanation of dataset

  • eco - ECO codes is a classification system for chess opening moves. Chess openings can be divided into five volumes from â€œAâ€ through â€œEâ€.

  • white_elo - The Elo rating system is a technique to calculate the relative skill levels of players compared to other players. Most chess Grandmasters have an Elo rating of 2500 and above. 68% of players are at the Grandmaster level.

  • result - This indicates whether the winner is â€˜whiteâ€™, â€˜blackâ€™ or â€˜drawâ€™. 1-0 = white winner, 1/2-1/2 = draw, 0-1 = black winner.

  • elo_difference - This tells us the difference in Elo between the two players which is an indication of the difference in skill level.

  • eco_cat - ECO is categorised into different groups.

Data preprocessing

Since chess Elos are not linear (i.e., the difference between 2700 and 2800 is greater than the difference between 1900 and 2000), we will calculate the z-score of each player and raise â€˜eâ€™ to that z-score.

Z-score provides how many standard deviations away a value is from the mean.

Creating adjusted elo variable

# Create a dataframe containing all the Elo ratings to get the mean and standard deviation
tmp <- data.frame(wizards_chess$white_elo, wizards_chess$black_elo)
tmp <- stack(tmp)
mean_elo = mean(tmp[,1])
sd_elo = sd(tmp[,1])

# Calculating z-scores and raise 'e' to the z-scores
wizards_chess$adjusted_white_elo <- exp(pnorm(wizards_chess$white_elo, mean_elo, sd_elo))
wizards_chess$adjusted_black_elo <- exp(pnorm(wizards_chess$black_elo, mean_elo, sd_elo))
wizards_chess$adjusted_elo_difference <- wizards_chess$adjusted_white_elo - wizards_chess$adjusted_black_elo

Creating winner variable

# Set win to 1-0, lose to 0-1
win = " 1-0"
lose = " 0-1"

# Generate a new variable called winner that assigns 1-0 to white wins, 0-1 to black wins, and 1/2-1/2 to a draw
wizards_chess <- mutate(wizards_chess, winner = ifelse(result==win,"white",ifelse(result==lose,"black","draw")))

# Make the column a factor
wizards_chess$winner = as.factor(wizards_chess$winner)

table(wizards_chess$winner, wizards_chess$result)
##        
##            *  0-1  1-0  1/2-1/2
##   black    0 3129    0        0
##   draw     2    0    0     7950
##   white    0    0 4584        0

Modelling Part 1 - Multinomial logistic regression

We use multinomial regression since we have three outcomes: white win, black win and draw

# Splitting the data into the train and test datasets
# 70% for train and 30% for test

id = sample(1:nrow(wizards_chess), .3 * nrow(wizards_chess))
dataset.test <- wizards_chess[id,]
dataset.train <- wizards_chess[-id,]

# Create the multinomial model for the train dataset
model1 <- multinom(winner ~ adjusted_elo_difference + eco_cat + adjusted_white_elo + adjusted_black_elo, dataset.train)

Use the stepAIC function to choose a model by AIC in a stepwise algorithm. stepAIC is used for feature selection, essentially to simplify the model without impacting its performance.
AIC quantifies the amount of information loss due to this simplification.
AIC = Akaike Information Criteria.

model1 <- stepAIC(model1, direction = "both") #MASS package

Modelling Part 2 - Logistic regression (generalized linear models) on two outcomes

We will get rid of all the â€˜drawsâ€™ to see if the models would improve.

# Remove rows with draws
wizards_chess_sans_draw <- wizards_chess %>% filter(winner=="black" | winner=="white")

# Drop the draw level
wizards_chess_sans_draw = droplevels(wizards_chess_sans_draw)

# Create new train and test datasets
id = sample(1:nrow(wizards_chess_sans_draw), .3 * nrow(wizards_chess_sans_draw))
dataset.test <- wizards_chess_sans_draw[id,]
dataset.train <- wizards_chess_sans_draw[-id,]
model2 <- glm(winner ~ adjusted_elo_difference + eco_cat + adjusted_white_elo + adjusted_black_elo, family = binomial(link = "logit"),dataset.train)

# feature selection
model2 <- stepAIC(model2, direction = "both")

Modelling Part 3 - Gradient Boosting Machine

Gradient boosting is a kind of machine learning boosting, which is a method for creating an ensemble. An ensemble is a combination of individual models. Machine learning boosting starts from fitting an initial model to th data. Then another model is built to focus on predicting the cases that performed poorly in the first model. This boosting process is repeated many times and each successive model attempts to overcome the shortcomings of the combined boosted ensemble.

# 5 fold cross validiation
fitControl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 5,repeats = 1)

# Generate GBM model

model3 <- train(winner ~ adjusted_elo_difference + eco_cat  + adjusted_white_elo + adjusted_black_elo, data=dataset.train, method = "gbm", trControl = fitControl, verbose = FALSE)

# Accuracy for train dataset
confusionMatrix(predict(model3, newdata = dataset.train), dataset.train$winner)

Modelling Part 4 - Decision tree

Decision trees are an alternative to logistic regression which allows easy intrepretation of results.

# decision tree train dataset

model4 <- rpart(winner~adjusted_elo_difference + eco_cat + adjusted_white_elo + adjusted_black_elo, method="class", data=dataset.train)

predict_fit = predict(model4, dataset.train)

predicted_winner = data.frame(winner = predict_fit[,1])

predicted_winner[,1] <- colnames(predict_fit)[apply(predict_fit,1,which.max)]

confusionMatrix(as.factor(predicted_winner[,1]), as.factor(dataset.train$winner), positive = "white")

The overall chances of white winning at the top is 59%.
Then the node asked whether the adjusted elo difference is more or less than 0.041. If the answer is yes, then follow the root nodeâ€™s left child node. 52% had an adjusted elo difference of < 0.041, and the probability of black winning is 44%.
